english:
  title: A Refutation of the Story of the Cracked Steamer in Du Mu's Biography
  author: Lee Gyu-bo
  language: eng
  text: |-
    In Du Mu's biography, there is a tale: when Du Mu lay dying, his cooking steamer cracked, and Du Mu said, 'This is inauspicious.' I offer this refutation:

    This is merely the superstitious prattle of shamans and fortune-tellers clinging to numerology and divination. That Du Mu would speak of inauspiciousness is unbecoming of a true scholar. The historian Song Gong should have omitted this passage from his account, yet he recorded it—surely a flaw in his judgment. The Book of History teaches: 'When the hen crows at dawn, the household faces ruin.' Yet hens have no natural duty to crow at dawn; when they do so, it is the household's abnormality, not the universe's condemnation. Such portents—the pheasant shrieking at the cauldron, the rat dancing at the palace gate—are far greater prodigies. Thus the Sage preserved these accounts rather than deleting them.

    But a cracked steamer? It splits either from excessive heat or from drying too quickly—hardly a marvel. That Du Mu's death coincided with the steamer's breaking is mere chance, no reliable omen.

    Consider my own experience: Last autumn in the ninth month, my steamer cracked with a sharp sound while cooking. I gave it no thought of calamity. This very year in the second month, it emitted a sound like an ox's bellow, then split wide open as if cleaved by a blade. My serving woman went pale with fear and rushed to tell me. I only smiled. A diviner happened to arrive and declared, 'This portends ill for the master. Without prayer and appeasement, disaster may not be averted.' My wife wished to comply at once, but I stopped her, saying: 'Life and death follow Heaven's decree. If my time has come, what good are prayers? If it has not, what harm can a broken steamer do?' Yet here I remain, alive to this day.

    So tell me—why did Du Mu perish from a single cracked steamer, while I survive two? By what misfortune did he lack grace, by what virtue do I possess it? This proves no reliable correspondence between sign and fate. I write this lest posterity be seduced by such superstitions.
  footnotes:
    - Du Mu (803-852) was a celebrated Tang Dynasty poet and official whose biography appears in historical records.
    - The Book of History reference reflects Confucian thought on prodigies and their proper interpretation.
    - Lee Gyu-bo employs rational Confucian skepticism to challenge folk superstition and interpretive credulity in historical writing.
